### Changes made

**`src/llama-chat.h`** — new enum value inserted before `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_UNKNOWN`:
```cpp
LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3,
```

**`src/llama-chat.cpp`** — three additive insertions:

**① Map entry** (string → enum lookup for explicit `-ctk mistral-instruct-v3`):
```cpp
{ "mistral-instruct-v3", LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3 },
```

**② Auto-detection** (inside the `[INST]` branch's `else` block, before the llama2 checks):
```cpp
// mistral-instruct-v3: uses [INST]/[/INST] without [SYSTEM_PROMPT]
// (absence of [SYSTEM_PROMPT] distinguishes it from the Ministral 3 / MISTRAL_V7 handler)
// identified by the raise_exception usage present in the official v0.3 template
if (tmpl_contains("raise_exception")) {
    return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3;
}
```

The detection works because the outer `[INST]` branch already filtered out `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` (→ `MISTRAL_V7`) and `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]`/`system_message` concatenation (→ V1/V3/V3-TEKKEN). `raise_exception` is present in the official Mistral v0.3 Jinja template but absent from all llama2-family templates, making it the right positive discriminator.

**③ Handler** (new `else if` block before the terminal `else { return -1; }`):
```cpp
} else if (tmpl == LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3) {
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 format: user turns wrapped with [INST]/[/INST],
    // system message prepended to the first user turn, </s> appended after assistant turns.
    std::string pending_system;
    for (auto message : chat) {
        std::string role(message->role);
        std::string content(message->content);
        if (role == "system") {
            pending_system = content + "\n\n";
        } else if (role == "user") {
            ss << "[INST] " << pending_system << content << " [/INST]";
            pending_system.clear();
        } else {
            ss << content << "</s>";
        }
    }
}
```

The `pending_system` string accumulates any system message and flushes it (with a `\n\n` separator) when the first user turn is encountered, producing the correct `[INST] {system}\n\n{user} [/INST]` format. Assistant turns emit `{content}</s>` exactly as the v0.3 format specifies.

